---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "irc:// — a discovery standard for modern IRC";
const description =
  "A tiny discovery standard (.well-known/irc.json) and reference client that makes modern IRC as easy to adopt as a podcast feed. Free and self-hostable; subscription is bridge funding for protocol adoption, not a moat.";

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Person",
  name: "David W. Keith",
  url: "https://dwk.io",
  sameAs: ["https://dwk.io"],
  worksFor: {
    "@type": "Project",
    name: "irc://",
    url: "https://irc.dwk.io",
  },
};

const lastModified = "2026-04-24";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <h1>A discovery standard for modern IRC</h1>

  <p>
    IRC never crossed the chasm to mass use because onboarding is technical,
    not because the protocol is bad. Modern <a
      href="https://ircv3.net/"
      rel="external">IRCv3</a> has quietly solved the hard parts —
    <a href="https://ircv3.net/specs/extensions/chathistory" rel="external">chathistory</a>,
    <a href="https://github.com/ircv3/ircv3-specifications/pull/471" rel="external">web push</a>,
    <a href="https://github.com/ircv3/ircv3-specifications/pull/435" rel="external">account registration</a>,
    <a href="https://ircv3.net/wg" rel="external">WebSockets transport</a> — but no client or
    discovery mechanism puts them together in a way an ordinary person can
    follow from "site I'm visiting" to "in the conversation."
  </p>

  <p>
    The <span class="wordmark">irc://</span> project proposes a tiny
    discovery standard at <code>/.well-known/irc.json</code> and ships a
    reference client built on modern IRCv3, so any website can host a
    first-class community chat with the onboarding friction of subscribing
    to a podcast.
  </p>

  <h2>The spec triangle</h2>

  <p>
    Three sibling JSON formats. Each can be implemented independently;
    together they handle discovery, browse, and composable trust.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong><code>application/irc+json</code></strong> at
      <code>/.well-known/irc.json</code> — a community publishes this on
      their own origin to advertise their IRC presence (network, channels,
      required capabilities, governance metadata).
      <a href="/spec/well-known-irc-json/">Read the spec →</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>application/irc-directory+json</code></strong> at
      <code>/.well-known/irc-directory.json</code> — a curator publishes
      this to advertise a list of networks. Multiple directories per
      client; project ships no default subscription.
      <a href="/spec/irc-directory-json/">Read the spec →</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>application/irc-trust-list+json</code></strong> at
      <code>/.well-known/irc-trust-list.json</code> — a curator publishes
      block, warn, vouch, flag, and annotate entries about networks,
      channels, accounts, and domains. Composable across many curators
      with full attribution; modeled on Matrix
      <a href="https://github.com/the-draupnir-project/Draupnir" rel="external">Draupnir</a>.
      <a href="/spec/irc-trust-list-json/">Read the spec →</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Principles</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>IndieNet protocol fidelity.</strong> <code>irc://</code> for
      chat, <code>mailto:</code> for mail, <code>https://</code> for pages.
      No central redirector. Each domain owner teaches their own users.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Free protocol, paid convenience.</strong> Anything the
      protocol can do, the reference client does for free. Subscription
      revenue is bridge funding for the standards work, not the long-term
      business.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Permissively licensed, designed to be commoditized.</strong>
      All code is <a href="https://opensource.org/license/isc-license-txt" rel="external">ISC-licensed</a>;
      spec text and schemas are released under
      <a href="https://creativecommons.org/public-domain/cc0/" rel="external">CC0</a>.
      Anyone — competitor, hyperscaler, hosting provider — can fork,
      rehost, rebrand, or bundle this into another subscription. That is
      the goal, not a tolerated side effect.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Composable trust, no arbiter.</strong> Safety signals are
      composed from mechanical checks plus the user's chosen trust lists.
      The project is not the referee.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Status</h2>

  <p>
    All three specifications and their JSON Schemas exist as v0.1 drafts.
    IANA media-type, well-known-URI, and link-relation registrations are
    drafted and ready to socialize in <code>#ircv3</code> on Libera before
    submission. Reference client (Apple-platform, Swift/SwiftUI) is in
    build prep. Looking for the first civic or institutional adopter.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/davidwkeith/irc-::" rel="external">Source on GitHub</a>
  </p>

  <hr />

  <p>
    <span class="timestamp">Last-Modified: {lastModified}</span>
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
